.TH CONDUIT 1 "2026-04-04" "Conduit 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
conduit \- network relay with process masquerading
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B conduit
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fI<address1>\fR \fI<address2>\fR
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B Conduit
is a network relay tool with integrated process masquerading capabilities, built on SOCAT 1.7.3.3. It provides secure data tunneling with stealth features for authorized security testing and defensive operations.
.PP
Conduit establishes bidirectional byte streams between two addresses and transfers data between them. Addresses can be files, pipes, devices, sockets, or other stream-like endpoints.
.SH OPTIONS
.SS Stealth Options
.TP
.B \-Ms
Masquerade as systemd service (systemd-logind)
.TP
.B \-MS
Masquerade as SSH daemon (/usr/sbin/sshd)
.TP
.B \-Mn
Masquerade as NetworkManager
.TP
.B \-Md
Masquerade as dbus-daemon
.TP
.B \-Mr
Masquerade as systemd-resolved
.TP
.BI \-Mc " name"
Masquerade with custom process name
.TP
.BI \-Mp " pid"
Target specific PID by manipulating /proc/sys/kernel/ns_last_pid (Linux only, requires root or CAP_SYS_ADMIN). Forks a child process that will attempt to receive the specified PID. The parent process automatically restores the original ns_last_pid value and exits. Useful for blending into specific PID ranges or mimicking service restart behavior.
.TP
.B \-Mo
Enable OOM (Out-Of-Memory) immunity by setting /proc/self/oom_score_adj to -1000. This prevents the Linux OOM killer from terminating the process under memory pressure. Useful for persistent operations that should not be killed during low-memory conditions.
.TP
.BI \-MP " range"
Set ephemeral port range for outbound connections by writing to /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_local_port_range. Format: low-high (e.g., 49152-65535). Useful for blending with standard ephemeral port allocation patterns or targeting specific port ranges. Requires root or CAP_NET_ADMIN.
.TP
.B \-Me
Sanitize environment variables by removing suspicious entries that could reveal the process origin. Removes: SSH_CONNECTION, SSH_CLIENT, SSH_TTY, SUDO_USER, SUDO_UID, SUDO_GID, SUDO_COMMAND, DISPLAY, XAUTHORITY, _, OLDPWD. Useful for removing forensic artifacts from the process environment.
.SS Standard SOCAT Options
.TP
.B \-V
Print version and feature information to stdout, and exit
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-?
Print help text describing command line options and addresses
.TP
.B \-hh
Like \-h, plus a list of all common address option names
.TP
.B \-hhh
Like \-hh, plus a list of all available address option names
.TP
.B \-d[\fIdddd\fR]
Increase verbosity (use up to 4 times; 2 are recommended)
.TP
.B \-D
Analyze file descriptors before loop
.TP
.B \-ly[\fIfacility\fR]
Log to syslog, using facility (default is daemon)
.TP
.BI \-lf logfile
Log to file
.TP
.B \-ls
Log to stderr (default if no other log)
.TP
.B \-lm[\fIfacility\fR]
Mixed log mode (stderr during initialization, then syslog)
.TP
.BI \-lp progname
Set the program name used for logging
.TP
.B \-lu
Use microseconds for logging timestamps
.TP
.B \-lh
Add hostname to log messages
.TP
.B \-v
Verbose data traffic, text
.TP
.B \-x
Verbose data traffic, hexadecimal
.TP
.BI \-b size
Set data buffer size (8192)
.TP
.B \-s
Sloppy (continue on error)
.TP
.BI \-t timeout
Wait seconds before closing second channel
.TP
.BI \-T timeout
Total inactivity timeout in seconds
.TP
.B \-u
Unidirectional mode (left to right)
.TP
.B \-U
Unidirectional mode (right to left)
.TP
.B \-g
Do not check option groups
.TP
.BI \-L " lockfile"
Try to obtain lock, or fail
.TP
.BI \-W " lockfile"
Try to obtain lock, or wait
.TP
.B \-4
Prefer IPv4 if version is not explicitly specified
.TP
.B \-6
Prefer IPv6 if version is not explicitly specified
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B TCP port forwarding with systemd masquerade
conduit \-Ms TCP-LISTEN:8080,fork,reuseaddr TCP:target.internal:80
.TP
.B HTTPS relay with systemd masquerade
conduit \-Ms TCP-LISTEN:443,fork TCP:backend:443
.TP
.B Custom process name
conduit \-Mc "[ksoftirqd/0]" TCP-LISTEN:22 TCP:real-ssh:22
.TP
.B UDP relay with daemon masquerade
conduit \-Md UDP-LISTEN:53,fork UDP:8.8.8.8:53
.TP
.B Reverse shell relay
conduit \-Mr TCP-LISTEN:4444 EXEC:/bin/bash
.TP
.B Target specific PID (requires root)
sudo conduit \-Ms \-Mp 500 TCP-LISTEN:8080 TCP:target:80
.TP
.B OOM immunity for persistent relay
sudo conduit \-Ms \-Mo TCP-LISTEN:443,fork TCP:backend:443
.TP
.B Port range control with environment sanitization
sudo conduit \-Ms \-MP 49152-65535 \-Me TCP-LISTEN:8080 TCP:target:80
.SH ADDRESS TYPES
Conduit supports all standard SOCAT address types including:
.PP
TCP, TCP-LISTEN, UDP, UDP-LISTEN, UNIX-CONNECT, UNIX-LISTEN, EXEC, SYSTEM, PIPE, STDIO, FILE, GOPEN, INTERFACE, IP4-SENDTO, IP6-SENDTO, OPENSSL, OPENSSL-LISTEN, PROXY, PTY, READLINE, SCTP-CONNECT, SCTP-LISTEN, SOCKS4, SOCKS4A, TUN
.PP
For full address documentation, see the SOCAT manual or use:
.br
.B conduit \-h
.SH SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS
.PP
Process masquerading modifies the process name visible in system monitoring tools (ps, top, etc.) to blend network operations with legitimate system processes. This is intended for:
.IP \(bu 2
Authorized penetration testing
.IP \(bu 2
Red team operations with written authorization
.IP \(bu 2
CTF competitions
.IP \(bu 2
Defensive security operations
.IP \(bu 2
Educational purposes
.PP
.B Unauthorized use is prohibited and may be illegal in your jurisdiction.
.PP
Conduit inherits all security features and considerations from SOCAT, including SSL/TLS support, certificate validation, and secure socket options.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /usr/local/bin/conduit
Default installation location
.SH NOTES
Conduit is a derivative work of SOCAT 1.7.3.3 by Gerhard Rieger and contributors. All SOCAT features and address types are supported.
.PP
Process masquerading uses platform-native APIs:
.IP \(bu 2
Linux: prctl(PR_SET_NAME)
.IP \(bu 2
BSD/macOS: setproctitle()
.PP
Argument hiding is automatic for all operations to prevent disclosure via process listings.
